                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="86834" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Wed, 16 Jan 2013 02:37:36 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I&apos;m afraid that this is how the feature has been designed: The default value will be applied immediately whenever the placeholder is being parsed.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We generally don&apos;t recommend multiple PropertyPlaceholderConfigurers to process the very same placeholders. I&apos;d rather expect different placeholder prefixes to be used there. Otherwise, why not simply use a unified property source?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="87007" author="ryanw" created="Thu, 17 Jan 2013 18:14:21 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;@Juergen, we want to use multiple PropertyPlaceholderConfigurers in our multi-module project so that we can have a properties file for each module.  This makes integration testing much easier because no module needs to look at another module&apos;s properties.  Each module can look at its own classpath for properties.  e.g.  in our &apos;data&apos; module we have &apos;data.properties&apos;.  So for integration tests in the data module we have a PropertyPlaceHolderConfigurer that looks at classpath:data.properties.  We do the same thing for our &apos;service&apos; and &apos;web&apos; modules.  The problem is that multiple PropertyPlaceHolderConfigurers when loaded altogether in the same context doesn&apos;t appear to work.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="87008" author="ryanw" created="Thu, 17 Jan 2013 18:17:16 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;@Juergen, you mention not using PropertyPlaceholderConfigurers for the very same placeholders.  I agree with that.  This problem appears for us even if the PropertyPlaceholderConfigurers have different placeholders.  (But we are using them inside a nested &amp;lt;beans&amp;gt; element so perhaps that is the root cause and deserves a separate bug report.)&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
